Australia's Stocks Slump 20% From 2010 Peak After U.S. Credit Rating Cut

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-08-08T07:16:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-08/australia-stocks-near-20-fall-from-peak-after-u-s-downgrade.html
Australian stocks plunged, dragging
the nation’s key index down 20 percent from its April 2010 peak,
after  Standard & Poor’s  cut the U.S. credit rating, fueling
concern a global economic recovery will stall.  Billabong International Ltd. (BBG) , the world’s biggest surfwear
maker that gets almost half its sales from the Americas, dropped
4.2 percent.  James Hardie Industries SE (JHX) , the No. 1 seller of
home siding in the U.S., lost 3.2 percent.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) ,
the world’s No. 1 mining company, sank 4 percent after commodity
prices tumbled. Commonwealth Bank of  Australia , the nation’s
largest lender by market value, lost 1.4 percent, paring losses
after the Group of Seven nations pledged to support financial
stability.  Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index, which last week had its
steepest weekly retreat since 2008, fell 2.9 percent to 3,986.10
at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading in Sydney. tocks. The gauge
has fallen 20 percent from the peak it reached on April 15, 2010,
after climbing from its March 6, 2009, low in the aftermath of
the global financial crisis.  New Zealand ’s NZX 50 Index lost 2.8
percent to 3,185.45 at the 5 p.m. close n Wellington, dragging
the benchmark down 11 percent from its May 20 high.  The U.S. downgrade “has added another significant issue
for the global economy and stock markets to overcome,” said  Tim Schroeders , who helps manage $1 billion in equities at Pengana
Capital Ltd. in Melbourne. “The risks remain to the downside
for economic growth, with a re-pricing of U.S borrowings likely
to impose a higher cost of capital in the future.”  Politics Blamed       Australia’s key index has lost 16 percent this year,
compared with drops of 4.6 percent by the  S&P 500  and 13.4
percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the Australian
benchmark are valued at 10.6 times estimated earnings on average,
compared with 12 times for the S&P 500 and 9.8 times for the
Stoxx 600.  S&P announced the one-level reduction in the U.S.’s
sovereign-debt rating to AA+ on Aug. 5. The Treasury Department
said there is “no justifiable rationale” for S&P’s move, while
S&P’s officials stood by their decision and laid blame on a
political system that failed to adequately address deficit
reduction in the compromise law that President Barack Obama
signed this month to avert a default.  Billabong dropped 4.2 percent to A$5.06.  James Hardie  lost
3.2 percent to A$5.10.  Qantas Airways Ltd. (QAN) , Australia’s biggest
airline, sank 5.6 percent to A$1.595.  Oil Falls  Crude oil for September delivery fell as much as 4.3
percent today on the  New York  Mercantile Exchange, while a
measure of primary metals, including copper and aluminum,
dropped 3.7 percent on Aug. 5. Copper futures in New York sank
as much as 2.2 percent today.  BHP fell 4 percent to A$36.60. Rio Tinto Group, the world’s
second-biggest mining company, dropped 4.7 percent to A$68.63 in
Sydney, set for the lowest closing price in more than a year.
Rio and Mitsubishi Corp. offered A$1.49 billion ($1.55 billion)
for the shares in Coal & Allied Industries Ltd. they don’t own
to take the coal miner private.  “Sentiment will take a hit from the U.S. downgrade, and
equities markets in particular are the preferred venue for the
expression of panic,” said Prasad Patkar, who helps manage the
equivalent of $1.7 billion at Sydney-based Platypus Asset
Management Ltd. “It’ll take another globally-coordinated effort
by central banks and regulators to allay concerns about the
knock-on impacts, which means a prolonged period of uncertainty  Commonwealth Bank of Australia (CBA)  lost 1.4 percent to A$45.62
following the G-7 statement. It erased a loss of as much as 2.2
percent earlier after the  European Central Bank  also indicated
it will buy Italian and Spanish bonds in a bid to contain
Europe’s debt crisis.  To contact the reporters on this story:
